      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, i'm having some trouble with my sourdough. the starter is super inconsistent lately. can u explain the actual science of how the wild yeast and lactobacilli actually interact with temperature and hydration to produce the CO2? like what's happening at a microscopic level to make it rise?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The sourdough starter's inconsistency is a common issue, but it's fascinating to dive into the microscopic world of yeast and bacteria interaction. The wild yeast and lactobacilli in your starter are like a tiny, microbial society, working together to produce CO2. As the temperature and hydration levels change, the yeast and bacteria adapt and interact in complex ways. \n\nAt the microscopic level, yeast cells like Saccharomyces cerevisiae and lactobacilli like Lactobacillus sanfranciscensis produce enzymes that break down the sugars in the dough. This process is called glycolysis, and it releases electrons, which are then used to generate ATP (adenosine triphosphate), the energy currency of the cell. As the yeast and bacteria feed on the sugars, they produce CO2 as a byproduct of cellular respiration.\n\nNow, the temperature and hydration levels in your starter affect the rate of glycolysis and cellular respiration. Warmer temperatures (around 75°F to 80°F) stimulate yeast growth and fermentation, while cooler temperatures (around 65°F to 70°F) slow it down. Similarly, higher hydration levels (around 70% to 80%) favor yeast growth,",
